  "summary": "Josephine returns home with a head bandage, but despite Madge's suggestion that she rest, Josephine insists on visiting her fish at the pond. During this time, Josephine admits she knew about the will leaving Aristide's assets to Sophia because she had been eavesdropping. She also reveals she suspected Brenda and Lawrence were involved in something suspicious after observing Lawrence hiding items in the water closet, noting that he did not appear to be performing plumbing repairs.\n\nEdith de Harvilland, appearing exhausted and dejected, summons Josephine and later speaks with the narrator. Edith expresses a desire for Brenda to receive a fair legal defense, despite her previous dislike for her, though she remains indifferent toward Lawrence. When the narrator mentions his plan to drive to London, Edith asks to accompany him, requesting to be dropped off at Debenham Street and Harley Street to avoid traveling with Margaret and Sophia.\n\nSeeking further information, the narrator meets with Inspector Taverner. Taverner explains that while the case against Brenda and Lawrence is strong, the evidence is largely circumstantial. He notes that the incriminating love letters found behind the sink imply a conspiracy to be together following the husband's death, but a defense lawyer could argue the letters merely refer to an expected natural death. Taverner concludes that the outcome of the case depends on whether the jury views the pair as sympathetic individuals or as a typical criminal duo.",
